&gt; It depends on what radiation you&#39;re talking about,  the electronic
&gt; equipment and what it&#39;s made of.
&gt;
&gt; EMP (electromagnetic pulse) generated at the time of a nuclear detonation
&gt; will probably wipe out any solid-state electronics that isn&#39;t heavily
&gt; shielded against it. Alpha and beta particles could affect some electronics
&gt; that managed to survive an EMP.
&gt;
&gt; The older stuff like RTL and TTL logic is probably not going to be much
&gt; affected by the alpha and beta radiation. CMOS devices, sensitive to static
&gt; discharges, would be next. VLSI chips have the greatest chance of being
&gt; affected (read: home computers). Vacuum tube circuits would hardly be
&gt; affected at all, even by EMP.
&gt; Strange that some of our oldest devices would be the last to go.
&gt; :-)
&gt;
&gt; Zack
